HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 871
By Martin B
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Dorris Parkins of Milan.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Dorris Parkins of Milan; and
WHEREAS, Dorris Parkins was an exemplary individual and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on April 5, 1932, Dorris Parkins was the daughter of Denton William
Fly and Esther Lee Rollins Fly and grew up working on her family farm while attending schools
in Milan; and
WHEREAS, at the age of seventeen, she was stricken with polio, which ended her
promising basketball career. With the aid of crutches, she graduated with her classmates,
attended college, and walked down the aisle with the love of her life, Bob Parkins; and
WHEREAS, the Parkinses' joyous marriage was blessed with the birth of eight healthy
children; and
WHEREAS, in 1965, Bob and Dorris Parkins founded the Milan Mirror newspaper; they
also owned and operated Green Acres Farm, which included over 300 dairy cows and a tomato
packing shed that employed hundreds and supplied some of the largest tomato producers in the
world; and
WHEREAS, an artist at heart, Dorris Parkins loved ceramics and porcelain so much that
she opened her own business, Dorris' Ceramics, in 1970; she held many classes there and
shared her passion for art with countless individuals from all over the region; and
WHEREAS, an active part of her community, Mrs. Parkins shared her time and talents
with the PTA, Freed-Hardeman College Associates, Graball Community Center, 4-H, and the
HJR0871
012513
- 1 -

YMCA, and she was recognized as a fifty-year member of the Daughters of the American
Revolution; and
WHEREAS, no stranger to awards and accolades, Dorris Parkins was named the Milan
Woman of the Year in 1982 by the Milan Chamber, the Woman of the Year by the Milan Garden
Club in 1971, and Mother of the Year by the Milan VFW in 1971 and was noted in Outstanding
Women in America; and
WHEREAS, perhaps her most prestigious recognition came in 1968, when Governor
Buford Ellington presented her with the coveted Governor's Trophy as Tennessee's
Handicapped Citizen of the Year; and
WHEREAS, the epitome of the Milan Community who has left a lasting legacy of grace
that will live on forever, Dorris Parkins was deeply devoted to her family, and she always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, a beloved family matriarch, Dorris Parkins is survived by her eight devoted
children, twelve cherished grandchildren, and a host of treasured great-grandchildren; and
WHEREAS, she was preceded in death by her husband of fifty-six years, Bob Parkins,
and her parents, Denton and Esther Fly; and
WHEREAS, Dorris Parkins leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all her chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional individual and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Dorris Parkins, reflecting fondly upon her
- 2 - 012513

impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mrs. Parkins.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
